<s> Quoting Tina Holmboe tina@greytower.net  </s>
<s> :  </s>
<s> The use of definition lists for general name/value pairs is a bit of a stretch of the semantics, but a common one (em, I thought, maybe I'm completely wrong on this).  </s>
<s> I've seen it similarly used for heirarchical data and it's only just occurring to me that perhaps this is HTML abuse.  </s>
<s> You mean my old-fashioned spelling of vit?? Well using the ligature in a Latin word seems correct to me from my very limited knowledge of Latin orthography.  </s>
<s> Using it in English words such as arch?ology is something I did once in what I realise now was a pretentious affectation, but still do because I'm used to it.  </s>
<s> So whether I'm being correct or pretentious depends on whether you consider "curriculum vit?/vitae" to be Latin or English derived from Latin.  </s>
<s> If the Americans can defend reducing ligatured ae and oe to a mere ugly e then I can much more easily defend retaining the ligature.  </s>
<s> I did worry about how it might appear given that I was looking for a job at the time I first wrote it and at the time google could find no English-language use of "curriculum vit?" rather than "curriculum vitae" though of course it could find plenty of uses of vit?  </s>
<s> (in particular with regards to Vatican documents).  </s>
<s> Now "curriculum vit?" appears to be a lot more common, I wonder if I've started a trend.  </s>
